  name: 'Bucktown',
  title: 'Roof Replacement in Bucktown Chicago',
  metaDescription: 'Roof replacement in Bucktown, Chicago. Vintage two-flat and greystone specialists, licensed contractors, free estimates, all roof types.',
  intro: 'Bucktown\'s Victorian-era two-flats and greystones on Maplewood, Leavitt, and Hoyne — immediately south of Wicker Park along the Milwaukee Avenue corridor — share the same 1880s-to-1910s building stock and mixed flat-plus-pitched roof profiles as their northern neighbors, with many properties now on their second post-renovation roofing cycle after 1990s-era work.',
  introEs: 'Los two-flats y greystones de la era victoriana de Bucktown en Maplewood, Leavitt y Hoyne — inmediatamente al sur de Wicker Park a lo largo del corredor de Milwaukee Avenue — comparten el mismo stock de construcción de los años 1880 a 1910 y perfiles de techo mixto plano e inclinado, con muchas propiedades ahora en su segundo ciclo de techado post-renovación después de trabajo de los años 90.',
  areaText: 'Bucktown (ZIP 60647) is immediately south of Wicker Park along the Milwaukee Avenue corridor, sharing its architectural character — dense Victorian-era two-flats, greystones, and renovated single-family homes. The neighborhood has seen sustained high property values and renovation activity, with many owners replacing roofing systems as part of larger rehab projects. Streets like Maplewood, Leavitt, and Hoyne have the vintage two-flats and greystones that dominate the older housing stock; the Western Avenue corridor has a mix of newer townhome developments. Flat roofs are common on the older two-flat stock; pitched asphalt shingle or metal roofs are common on renovated single-family homes. Bucktown sits in the Wicker Park-Bucktown Historic District, which may impose additional requirements on some landmark-designated properties. Typical replacement costs run $9,000 to $18,000 for single-family and $9,000 to $16,000 for two-flat flat roofs.',
  areaTextEs: 'Bucktown (ZIP 60647) está al sur de Wicker Park a lo largo del corredor de Milwaukee Avenue, con two-flats y greystones victorianos en calles como Maplewood, Leavitt y Hoyne. Los techos planos son comunes en los two-flats más antiguos. Los costos de reemplazo oscilan entre $9,000 y $18,000.',
  faq: [
    { q: 'How much does roof replacement cost in Bucktown in 2026?', a: 'Asphalt shingle replacement on a typical Bucktown single-family home or renovated greystone runs $9,000 to $18,000 depending on roof size, pitch, and material grade. Flat roof replacement on a Bucktown two-flat costs $9,000 to $16,000 for a TPO system. Metal roofing — popular among Bucktown owners planning long-term ownership — runs $18,000 to $28,000. All six listed contractors offer free on-site estimates.' },
    { q: 'Do Bucktown contractors work on vintage two-flats and greystones?', a: 'Yes. All contractors on our list have experience with the vintage two-flats and greystones common on Bucktown streets like Maplewood, Leavitt, and Hoyne. Many of these buildings have mixed profiles — flat membrane roofs on the rear and pitched sections at front — requiring two separate systems in the same project. Your contractor will assess both sections and provide separate line items during the free estimate.' },
    { q: 'Does the Wicker Park-Bucktown Historic District affect roof replacement?', a: 'For most residential properties in Bucktown, standard City of Chicago permits apply with no additional historic district requirements. However, some landmark-designated properties in the Wicker Park-Bucktown Historic District may require city approval of material selections before replacement begins. Your contractor will identify any landmark status during the free assessment. All listed contractors are familiar with Chicago\'s landmark permit process.' },
    { q: 'What roofing materials are popular in Bucktown?', a: 'Architectural asphalt shingles with Class 4 impact resistance are the most common choice for Bucktown\'s single-family and renovated properties. Metal roofing — particularly standing seam — is increasingly chosen by owners who plan to stay long term, given Bucktown\'s continued appreciation and the 40 to 70 year lifespan of metal systems. For two-flat flat roofs, TPO is the current standard. Composite slate-look shingles are also popular on Victorian properties where owners want to maintain the historic character.' },
    { q: 'My Bucktown two-flat needs a new flat roof. Should I use TPO or EPDM?', a: 'TPO is the recommended choice for new flat roof installations on Bucktown two-flats. TPO has a longer lifespan (25 to 35 years vs EPDM\'s 15 to 25), better heat reflectivity (lowers summer cooling costs on upper floors), and heat-welded seams that are more reliable than EPDM\'s adhesive seams in Chicago\'s freeze-thaw climate. TPO costs 10 to 20 percent more than EPDM upfront but typically costs less over the full lifecycle. EPDM remains a reasonable choice for landlords who need the lowest possible upfront cost.' },
    { q: 'Is a permit required for roof replacement in Bucktown?', a: 'Yes. The City of Chicago requires a building permit for all full roof replacements in Bucktown. All listed contractors pull this permit as part of every project at no extra charge. The permit is required regardless of whether your property is in the historic district. Skipping the permit creates code violations that appear at property sales — particularly important in Bucktown\'s active real estate market.' },
  ],
